 {"id":"remote_compilation_helper-w45","title":"SpeedScore Calculation and Normalization Engine","description":"## Overview
Implement the core SpeedScore calculation engine that combines individual benchmark results into a unified worker performance score, following the methodology from cloud_benchmarker but optimized for compilation workloads.

## Background and Justification
The SpeedScore provides a single, comparable metric for worker selection. Rather than requiring users to understand multiple metrics (CPU, memory, disk, network), they see one number that represents overall compilation capability.

Key insight from cloud_benchmarker: normalization is critical. Raw benchmark values vary by orders of magnitude (CPU in GFLOPS, disk in MB/s, latency in ms). We normalize everything to 0-100 scale before weighting.

## Implementation Details

### Core Structure
```rust
pub struct SpeedScore {
    /// Overall score (0-100)
    pub total: f64,

    /// Component scores (each 0-100)
    pub cpu_score: f64,
    pub memory_score: f64,
    pub disk_score: f64,
    pub network_score: f64,
    pub compilation_score: f64,

    /// Raw benchmark results for debugging/display
    pub raw_results: BenchmarkResults,

    /// Timestamp of benchmark run
    pub measured_at: DateTime<Utc>,

    /// Benchmark version (for invalidation on algorithm changes)
    pub version: u32,
}
```

### Normalization Function
```rust
/// Normalize a value to 0-100 scale using reference points
/// 
/// - `value`: The raw benchmark result
/// - `low_ref`: Value that maps to score 0 (poor performance)
/// - `high_ref`: Value that maps to score 100 (excellent performance)
/// - `higher_is_better`: true for throughput metrics, false for latency
fn normalize(value: f64, low_ref: f64, high_ref: f64, higher_is_better: bool) -> f64 {
    let normalized = if higher_is_better {
        (value - low_ref) / (high_ref - low_ref)
    } else {
        (low_ref - value) / (low_ref - high_ref)
    };
    (normalized * 100.0).clamp(0.0, 100.0)
}
```

### Reference Points (Calibrated for 2024-2026 Hardware)
| Benchmark | Low Ref (Score 0) | High Ref (Score 100) |
|-----------|-------------------|----------------------|
| CPU (GFLOPS) | 10 | 500 |
| Memory (GB/s) | 5 | 100 |
| Disk Seq (MB/s) | 100 | 5000 |
| Disk Random (IOPS) | 1000 | 500000 |
| Network (Mbps) | 100 | 10000 |
| Compilation (units/sec) | 10 | 200 |

### Weighting Strategy
Weights optimized for compilation workloads:
```rust
const WEIGHTS: SpeedScoreWeights = SpeedScoreWeights {
    cpu: 0.30,          // CPU-bound compilation
    memory: 0.15,       // Memory for large projects
    disk: 0.20,         // I/O for reading sources, writing objects
    network: 0.15,      // Transfer overhead
    compilation: 0.20,  // Real-world compilation performance
};
```

### Calculation
```rust
impl SpeedScore {
    pub fn calculate(results: &BenchmarkResults, weights: &SpeedScoreWeights) -> Self {
        let cpu_score = normalize(results.cpu.gflops, 10.0, 500.0, true);
        let memory_score = normalize(results.memory.bandwidth_gbps, 5.0, 100.0, true);
        let disk_score = (
            normalize(results.disk.sequential_read_mbps, 100.0, 5000.0, true) * 0.5 +
            normalize(results.disk.random_read_iops, 1000.0, 500000.0, true) * 0.5
        );
        let network_score = /* from network benchmark */;
        let compilation_score = normalize(results.compilation.units_per_sec, 10.0, 200.0, true);

        let total = 
            cpu_score * weights.cpu +
            memory_score * weights.memory +
            disk_score * weights.disk +
            network_score * weights.network +
            compilation_score * weights.compilation;

        Self { total, cpu_score, memory_score, disk_score, network_score, compilation_score, ... }
    }
}
```

